    return `Your prenatal appointments are so important — and knowing what to ask makes them even more valuable! 🩺 Here's your guide:

**Questions to Ask at Every Visit:**
• How is my baby's growth and development progressing?
• What is baby's current position?
• Are my weight and blood pressure within a healthy range?
• Are there any concerns from my last test results?
• What symptoms should prompt me to call you?

**First Trimester Questions:**
• What prenatal vitamins do you recommend?
• Are my current medications safe to continue?
• When should I have my first ultrasound and genetic screening?
• What foods and activities should I avoid?

**Second Trimester Questions:**
• Can we discuss my birth preferences and birth plan?
• Should I take a glucose tolerance test?
• When will we check baby's position?
• What exercises are safe at this stage?

**Third Trimester Questions:**
• What are the signs that I should go to the hospital?
• What is our plan if I go past my due date?
• Can we discuss pain management options during labor?
• What are the signs of preterm labor?

**Always Mention:**
• Any bleeding or spotting
• Severe headaches, vision changes, or facial swelling
• Reduced baby movements
• Painful or burning urination
• Any symptom that worries you — no question is too small!

Your doctor is your partner in this journey — ask everything! 💜`;
  if (/weight|gain/.test(m))
    return `Healthy weight gain is an important part of a thriving pregnancy! 📊 Here's what to know:

**Recommended Weight Gain by BMI:**
• Normal BMI (18.5–24.9): 11–16 kg total
• Underweight (under 18.5): 13–18 kg total
• Overweight (25–29.9): 7–11 kg total
• Obese (30+): 5–9 kg total
• Twin pregnancy: 17–25 kg total

**Healthy Gain Pattern:**
• First trimester: 0.5–2 kg (baby is tiny, gain is mostly body changes)
• Second trimester: approximately 0.5 kg per week
• Third trimester: approximately 0.5 kg per week
• Most weight gain is in the second and third trimesters

**Where Does the Weight Go?**
• Baby: approximately 3.4 kg
• Placenta: approximately 0.7 kg
• Amniotic fluid: approximately 0.9 kg
• Increased blood volume: approximately 1.8 kg
• Breast tissue growth: approximately 0.9 kg
• Body fat stores for birth and breastfeeding: 2.7–3.6 kg

**Tips for Healthy Weight Management:**
• Focus on nutrient density, not calorie restriction
• Eat regular, balanced meals with plenty of fruits and vegetables
• Stay active with pregnancy-safe exercise
• Avoid restrictive dieting — your baby needs steady nutrition
• Your midwife or doctor will monitor your gain at each visit

Every body is different — gain is nourishment, not a number to fear! 💜`;
  if (/vitamin|supplement|folic|iron|calcium/.test(m))
    return `Getting the right nutrients is one of the most powerful things you can do for your baby's development! 💊 Here's your complete supplement guide:

**Essential Supplements:**
• Folic Acid (400–800mcg) — prevents neural tube defects; take from preconception through week 12
• Iron (27mg daily) — prevents anemia and supports oxygen delivery to baby
• Calcium (1000mg) — builds strong bones and teeth for baby
• Vitamin D (600IU) — supports bone health, immunity, and mood
• DHA (200mg) — omega-3 for baby's brain and eye development
• Iodine (150mcg) — supports thyroid function and baby's brain development

**Best Food Sources:**
• Folic acid: spinach, lentils, asparagus, fortified cereals
• Iron: lean red meat, beans, tofu, dark leafy greens + Vitamin C to aid absorption
• Calcium: dairy, fortified plant milks, sardines, bok choy
• Vitamin D: fatty fish, egg yolks, fortified foods, safe sun exposure
• DHA: salmon, sardines, walnuts, flaxseed

**Tips for Taking Supplements:**
• Take prenatal vitamins with food to reduce nausea
• Take iron with orange juice (vitamin C boosts absorption)
• Don't take iron and calcium at the same time — they compete for absorption
• Talk to your doctor before adding any additional supplements
• A quality prenatal vitamin covers most of your needs

You're giving your baby the very best start in life! 🌟`;
  if (/mood|emotion|feeling sad|feeling|cry/.test(m))
    return `Pregnancy and motherhood come with a full spectrum of emotions — and every single one of them is valid. 💜 Here's some gentle support:

**Why Emotions Are Heightened:**
• Oestrogen and progesterone levels change dramatically during pregnancy
• Physical discomfort, sleep changes, and life adjustments all affect mood
• Anxiety about birth, parenting, and the future is completely normal
• Your identity is evolving — this is called matrescence, and it's real

**Nurturing Your Emotional Health:**
• Name your feelings without judgment — "I feel anxious" is okay
• Journaling: write freely for 5 minutes each morning
• Move your body gently — movement releases mood-lifting endorphins
• Connect with loved ones who make you feel safe and supported
• Prenatal yoga and meditation can help calm an anxious mind
• Limit news and social media — protect your mental space

**What Your Partner or Support Person Can Do:**
• Listen without trying to fix — sometimes you just need to be heard
• Take on practical tasks without being asked
• Celebrate small wins with you
• Remind you how capable and loved you are

**Seek Support If:**
• Sadness, anxiety, or irritability persists for more than 2 weeks
• You feel unable to bond with your baby
• You're having thoughts of harming yourself

You are doing something extraordinary — give yourself the grace you'd give a friend. 💜`;
